<article class="blog--container blog-preview">
<h2 class="blog--title">
<a href="/blog/2015/03/05/spring-data-release-train-fowler-rc1-available">Spring Data Release Train Fowler RC1 Available</a>
</h2>
<header class="meta-data--container">
<div class="meta-data--item desktop-only">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon releases"></div>
<a class="category" href="/blog/category/releases">Releases</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<img class="meta-data--icon" src="https://gravatar.com/avatar/eeacd6c45e867cb36eb05c9daa5cc2de?s=20&amp;d=mm" />
<a class="author" href="/team/christophstrobl">Christoph Strobl</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon calendar"></div>
<time class="date" pubdate="" datetime="2015-03-05 19:42:00.0">March 5, 2015</time>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon comments"></div>
<a class="comments" data-disqus-identifier="2009" href="/blog/2015/03/05/spring-data-release-train-fowler-rc1-available#disqus_thread">
</a></div>
</header>
<section class="blog--post desktop-only">
<div><p>I’m pleased to announce the availability of the first and final release candidate of the Spring Data release train named <a href="https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-data-commons/wiki/Release-Train-Fowler">Fowler</a>. The release ships <a href="https://jira.spring.io/issues/?filter=14932">149 tickets</a> fixed. Here are some of the highlights:</p>
<ul>
<li>Support for Java 8 <code>Stream</code> as return type in JPA and MongoDB.</li>
<li>Enhanced support for JSR-310 and the ThreeTen back port types.</li>
<li>Dedicated <a href="http://geojson.org">GeoJSON</a> types for the MongoDB module.</li>
<li>Compatibility with MongoDB 3.0 and the new MongoDB Java driver (current beta3).</li>
<li>Auto-populate the last modified header for audited entities in Spring Data REST.</li>
<li><code>@Score</code> annotation for Solr.</li>
<li>Support for suggestions in Elasticsearch.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</section>
<a class="blog-preview--readmore desktop-only" href="/blog/2015/03/05/spring-data-release-train-fowler-rc1-available">
Read more...
</a>
</article>
<article class="blog--container blog-preview">
<h2 class="blog--title">
<a href="/blog/2015/03/04/spring-cloud-1-0-0-available-now">Spring Cloud 1.0.0 Available Now</a>
</h2>
<header class="meta-data--container">
<div class="meta-data--item desktop-only">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon releases"></div>
<a class="category" href="/blog/category/releases">Releases</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<img class="meta-data--icon" src="https://gravatar.com/avatar/ae671230e3a1c2a0eefa7604990084f1?s=20&amp;d=mm" />
<a class="author" href="/team/dsyer">Dave Syer</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon calendar"></div>
<time class="date" pubdate="" datetime="2015-03-04 15:15:50.719">March 4, 2015</time>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon comments"></div>
<a class="comments" data-disqus-identifier="2008" href="/blog/2015/03/04/spring-cloud-1-0-0-available-now#disqus_thread">
</a></div>
</header>
<section class="blog--post desktop-only">
<div><p>Spring Cloud 1.0.0.RELEASE is available now in Maven Central (and repo.spring.io). Not too many changes since RC3 but we did find a few bugs, thanks largely to community involvement, so thanks to all who tried it out up to now. Here is a reminder of the goals of Spring Cloud:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Spring Cloud provides tools for developers to quickly build some of the common patterns in distributed systems (e.g. configuration management, service discovery, circuit breakers, intelligent routing, micro-proxy, control bus, one-time tokens, global locks, leadership election, distributed sessions, cluster state). Coordination of distributed systems leads to boiler plate patterns, and using Spring Cloud developers can quickly stand up services and applications that implement those patterns. They will work well in any distributed environment, including the developer’s own laptop, bare metal data centres, and managed platforms such as Cloud Foundry.</p>
</blockquote>
</div>
</section>
<a class="blog-preview--readmore desktop-only" href="/blog/2015/03/04/spring-cloud-1-0-0-available-now">
Read more...
</a>
</article>
